04723nam a22005895i 9780674273054DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222008mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742730547 a10.4159/97806742730542doi  a(DE-B1597)613967  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aDC138 7aHIS0130002bisacsh1 aGruder, Vivian R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Notables and the Nation :bThe Political Schooling of the French, 1787–1788 /cVivian R. Gruder. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (518 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHarvard Historical Studies ;v15700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tMap of France, 1786 -- tIntroduction -- tI. The Assembly of Notables: February–May 1787, November–December 1788 -- t1. Paths to Political Consciousness: The Notables in the First Assembly, February–May 1787 -- t2. Privilege, Property, and Participation: A Mutation in Elite Political Culture -- t3. The Society of Orders at Its Demise: The Vision of the Elite at the End of the Ancien Régime -- tII. The Media and the Public: Networks of Information, Opinion, Instruction -- t4. Political News as Coded Messages: The Parisian and Provincial Press, 1787–1788 -- t5. The Foreign French-Language Press: Gazettes -- t6. The Foreign French-Language Press: Journals of Opinion -- t7. Manuscript Newsletters—Nouvelles à la Main -- t8. Pamphlets and Other Writings: A Network of Political Education and Polemics -- t9. Readers and Reading Sites: The Public and the Network of the Printed and Written Media -- t10. The Verbal, the Visual, and the Festive -- tIII. At the Grass Roots -- t11. “Popular” Pamphlets: Political Messages to the Public -- t12. Can We Hear the Voices of Peasants? -- t13. The Grass Roots: Local Judges and Community Assemblies Speak Out -- tConclusion -- tAppendix A. Chronology -- tAppendix B. Contemporary Accounts of Fêtes, 1787–1788 -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe ending of absolute, centralized monarchy and the beginning of political combat between nobles and commoners make the years 1787 to 1788 the first stage of the French Revolution. In a detailed examination of this critical transition, Vivian Gruder examines how the French people became engaged in a movement of opposition that culminated in demands for the public's role in government. Gruder traces the growing involvement of the French people in the public issues of the day, leading to increased politicization. The debates of the Assembly of Notables in early 1787 aroused public support against the monarchy and in late 1788 confirmed public opposition to the nobility. The media--including newspapers and newsletters, pamphlets, literary societies, songs, iconography, and festive activities--disseminated messages of opposition and gave voice to popular aspirations for change. At hundreds of community assemblies throughout France in late 1788, people showed remarkable astuteness about such political issues as voting and representation and demonstrated a capacity for mobilization.The Notables and the Nation contributes to a renewed interest in the political origins of the French Revolution. It argues that a "bourgeois" revolution did take place as a movement for political aspirations, and invites us to witness the birth of popular representative government.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674273054423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674273054/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_